<TR BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=3><TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=15&show_all=1"><font size=2>&lt;&lt;&lt;&nbsp;DEC&nbsp;15</font></a></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl"><font size=2>HOME</font></a></TD><TD ALIGN="CENTER"><a class="addthis_button" href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"><img src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif" width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://s7.addthis.com/js/250/addthis_widget.js#pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"></script></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="RIGHT"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=17&show_all=1"><font size=2>DEC&nbsp;17&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR>
<TR HEIGHT=5><TD COLSPAN=3 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_16.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_16.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>AFTERBURNER</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>9 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
Back before rollerblading and those strange shoes which have heels you
can click out and slide on (well, kids can - I don't think they come
in adult size twelves, do they?), the big fad when I was a kid was
rollerskating. Every year at school, the whole year used to be taken on
a school trip to the local rollerdisco, and unlike most physical
sports, I was actually a bit OK at this. My technique was fearless as
<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=200 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d16_1988_ad2.png" target="1988_ad2.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d16_1988_ad2_small.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=287></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>By 1989 the hype machine was in full flow - teaser ads were expected, but usually exciting.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
I went zooming through the straights before taking on the oval's turn
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/h24CFZqSEAA&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/h24CFZqSEAA&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Gremlins Trailer</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Festive chainsaws and crossbows... <b><i>(2:09)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h24CFZqSEAA" target="h24CFZqSEAA">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

and making the corner a good, oooh, six times out of ten. My stopping
technique was legendary - rather than taking an age slowing down
around the oval, or banging into the side, or letting gravity take its
course in the middle of the oval, I'd aim myself into the entrance or
exit at full speed and let the surrounding carpet slow me down with
some force whilst weaving around ten-year-old kids wearing
deely-boppers.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The first time I did this, I noticed I was going past the amusement arcade.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;There.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I knew I could swing back to <i>Afterburner</i> from a start like that.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Anyway... this wasn't the full-on rotating <i>Afterburner</i> cockpit, just
the stand-up machine with the whacking great joystick and a platform
to stand on which I'm sure was meant to move, but either I was too
heavy for it, or it was broken. For our purposes, let us assume it's
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/Q8iOc_62DE4&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/Q8iOc_62DE4&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Top Of The Pops Christmas 1986</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">A bit of what was hot during 1986. <b><i>(8:21)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q8iOc_62DE4" target="Q8iOc_62DE4">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

the latter. For a crap gameplayer, <i>Afterburner</i> was a godsend as it had
a continue option when you got shot down too many times, so armed to
the teeth with pound coins, I kept blasting, rolling, shooting,
crashing and dodging through to the very end.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=300 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d16_1988_rev6.png" target="1988_rev6.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d16_1988_rev6_small.jpg" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=209></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>SU's review goes overboard, giving <i>Afterburner</i> the highest marks amongst the Speccy magazines, with a strangely early review featuring screenshots used in SU and C&VG preview features. Hmmmmm...</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
Hours seemed to pass. The huge screen, large rushing sprites, the loud
funky soundtrack, and the natty refuelling sequences where fully
engrossing, ensuring that I'd play right to the final "Mission
Accomplished" sequence at the very end. The rollerskating turned into
a pretext to play arcade games - the first time I went to the
rollerdisco, it wasn't <i>Afterburner</i> which hooked me into the arcade
hall, but <i>Paperboy</i>, complete with BMX handlebars, but I was truly crap
at that and went back to the skating.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="left"><TR><TD VALIGN="top"><TABLE  WIDTH=150 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d16_1988_pre2.png" target="1988_pre2.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d16_1988_pre2_small.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=214></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>That lush preview screenshot sadly lost a little detail in the final version of the game.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD VALIGN="top"><TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/JAIWTLal9e4&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/JAIWTLal9e4&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Smashie and Nicey - Christmas Is Charity</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Broadcast during Christmas 1992, this <i>just</i> counts as during the Speccy season, and it was too funny to miss! Catch Enfield and Whitehouse when they were funny! <b><i>(4:12)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JAIWTLal9e4" target="JAIWTLal9e4">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
</TD></TR></TABLE><i>Afterburner</i> on the Speccy was a true event in 1988, first being teased
in news articles in the Spring before nothing else being heard of it
until October, when everything just exploded. The first reports were
mouthwatering with magazine previewers writing that the game was being
written by Keith Burkhill, who was responsible for the astonishingly
fast <i>Space Harrier</i>. News that <i>Afterburner</i>'s game engine was just as
fast, together with the first mocked-up screenshots showing lush,
detailed graphics, made this game unmissable.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With a focussed marketing campaign and a final flourish of a
supplement given away with Crash's December issue, the scene was set
for one of Christmas' set pieces to arrive. It got mixed reviews, but I still contend that it's a fun game to play on the Speccy.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE><p>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
</TD><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
